# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: active-directory
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:active-directory/active-directory] A domain controller is a server running the **Active Directory Domain Services** (**AD DS**) role.
[src:active-directory/active-directory] It authenticates and authorizes all users and computers in a Windows domain-type network, assigning and enforcing security policies for all computers and installing or updating software.
[src:active-directory/active-directory] For example, when a user logs into a computer which is part of a Windows domain, Active Directory checks the submitted username and password and determines whether the user is a system administrator or a non-admin user.
[src:active-directory/active-directory] Active Directory uses Lightweight Directory Access Protocol (LDAP) versions 2 and 3, Microsoft's version of Kerberos, and DNS.
[src:active-directory/active-directory] Like many information-technology efforts, Active Directory originated out of a democratization of design using Requests for Comments (RFCs).
[src:active-directory/active-directory] The Internet Engineering Task Force (IETF) oversees the RFC process and has accepted numerous RFCs initiated by widespread participants.
[src:active-directory/active-directory] For example, LDAP underpins Active Directory.
[src:active-directory/active-directory] Also, X.500 directories and the Organizational Unit preceded the Active Directory concept that uses those methods.
[src:active-directory/active-directory] The LDAP concept began to emerge even before the founding of Microsoft in April 1975, with RFCs as early as 1971.
[src:active-directory/active-directory] RFCs contributing to LDAP include RFC 1823 (on the LDAP API, August 1995), RFC 2307, RFC 3062, and RFC 4533.
[src:active-directory/active-directory] Microsoft previewed Active Directory in 1999, released it first with Windows 2000 Server edition, and revised it to extend functionality and improve administration in Windows Server 2003.
[src:active-directory/active-directory] Active Directory support was also added to Windows 95, Windows 98, and Windows NT 4.0 via patch, with some unsupported features.
[src:active-directory/active-directory] Additional improvements came with subsequent versions of Windows Server.
[src:active-directory/active-directory] In Windows Server 2008, Microsoft added further services to Active Directory, such as Active Directory Federation Services.
[src:active-directory/active-directory] The part of the directory in charge of managing domains, which was a core part of the operating system, was renamed Active Directory Domain Services (ADDS) and became a server role like others.
[src:active-directory/active-directory] "Active Directory" became the umbrella title of a broader range of directory-based services.
[src:active-directory/active-directory] According to Byron Hynes, everything related to identity was brought under Active Directory's banner.
[src:active-directory/active-directory] Active Directory Services consist of multiple directory services.
[src:active-directory/active-directory] The best known is Active Directory Domain Services, commonly abbreviated as AD DS or simply AD.
[src:active-directory/active-directory] Active Directory Domain Services (AD DS) is the foundation of every Windows domain network.
[src:active-directory/active-directory] It stores information about domain members, including devices and users, verifies their credentials, and defines their access rights.
[src:active-directory/active-directory] The server running this service is called a domain controller.
[src:active-directory/active-directory] A domain controller is contacted when a user logs into a device, accesses another device across the network, or runs a line-of-business Metro-style app sideloaded into a machine.
[src:active-directory/active-directory] Other Active Directory services (excluding LDS, as described below) and most Microsoft server technologies rely on or use Domain Services; examples include Group Policy, Encrypting File System, BitLocker, Domain Name Services, Remote Desktop Services, Exchange Server, and SharePoint Server.
[src:active-directory/active-directory] The self-managed Active Directory DS must be distinct from managed Azure AD DS, a cloud product.
[src:active-directory/active-directory] Active Directory Lightweight Directory Services (AD LDS), previously called *Active Directory Application Mode* (ADAM), implements the LDAP protocol for AD DS.
[src:active-directory/active-directory] It runs as a service on Windows Server and offers the same functionality as AD DS, including an equal API.
[src:active-directory/active-directory] However, AD LDS does not require the creation of domains or domain controllers.
[src:active-directory/active-directory] It provides a Data Store for storing directory data and a *Directory Service* with an LDAP Directory Service Interface.
[src:active-directory/active-directory] Unlike AD DS, multiple AD LDS instances can operate on the same server.
[src:active-directory/active-directory] Active Directory Certificate Services (AD CS) establishes an on-premises public key infrastructure.
[src:active-directory/active-directory] It can create, validate, revoke and perform other similar actions, public key certificates for internal uses of an organization.
[src:active-directory/active-directory] These certificates can be used to encrypt files (when used with Encrypting File System), emails (per S/MIME standard), and network traffic (when used by virtual private networks, Transport Layer Security protocol or IPSec protocol).
[src:active-directory/active-directory] AD CS predates Windows Server 2008, but its name was simply Certificate Services.
[src:active-directory/active-directory] Active Directory Federation Services (AD FS) is a single sign-on service.
[src:active-directory/active-directory] AD FS uses many popular open standards to pass token credentials such as SAML, OAuth or OpenID Connect.
[src:active-directory/active-directory] AD FS supports encryption and signing of SAML assertions.
[src:active-directory/active-directory] AD FS's purpose is an extension of that of AD DS: The latter enables users to authenticate with and use the devices that are part of the same network, using one set of credentials.
[src:active-directory/active-directory] The former enables them to use the same set of credentials in a different network.
[src:active-directory/active-directory] As the name suggests, AD FS works based on the concept of federated identity.
[src:active-directory/active-directory] AD FS requires an AD DS infrastructure, although its federation partner may not.
[src:active-directory/active-directory] Active Directory is a service comprising a database and executable code.
[src:active-directory/active-directory] It is responsible for managing requests and maintaining the database.
[src:active-directory/active-directory] The Directory System Agent is the executable part, a set of Windows services and processes that run on Windows 2000 and later.
[src:active-directory/active-directory] Accessing the objects in Active Directory databases is possible through various interfaces such as LDAP, ADSI, messaging API, and Security Accounts Manager services.
[src:active-directory/active-directory] Active Directory structures consist of information about objects classified into two categories: resources (such as printers) and security principals (which include user or computer accounts and groups).
[src:active-directory/active-directory] Each security principal is assigned a unique security identifier (SID).
[src:active-directory/active-directory] An object represents a single entity, such as a user, computer, printer, or group, along with its attributes.
[src:active-directory/active-directory] Some objects may even contain other objects within them.
[src:active-directory/active-directory] Each object has a unique name, and its definition is a set of characteristics and information by a schema, which determines the storage in the Active Directory.
[src:active-directory/active-directory] Administrators can extend or modify the schema using the schema object when needed.
[src:active-directory/active-directory] However, because each schema object is integral to the definition of Active Directory objects, deactivating or changing them can fundamentally alter or disrupt a deployment.
[src:active-directory/active-directory] Modifying the schema affects the entire system automatically, and new objects cannot be deleted, only deactivated.
[src:active-directory/active-directory] Changing the schema usually requires planning.
[src:active-directory/active-directory] In an Active Directory network, the framework that holds objects has different levels: the forest, tree, and domain.
[src:active-directory/active-directory] Domains within a deployment contain objects stored in a single replicable database, and the DNS name structure identifies their domains, the namespace.
[src:active-directory/active-directory] A domain is a logical group of network objects such as computers, users, and devices that share the same Active Directory database.
[src:active-directory/active-directory] On the other hand, a tree is a collection of domains and domain trees in a contiguous namespace linked in a transitive trust hierarchy.
[src:active-directory/active-directory] The forest is at the top of the structure, a collection of trees with a standard global catalog, directory schema, logical structure, and directory configuration.
[src:active-directory/active-directory] The forest is a secure boundary that limits access to users, computers, groups, and other objects.
[src:active-directory/active-directory] The objects held within a domain can be grouped into organizational units (OUs).
[src:active-directory/active-directory] OUs can provide hierarchy to a domain, ease its administration, and can resemble the organization's structure in managerial or geographical terms.
[src:active-directory/active-directory] OUs can contain other OUs—domains are containers in this sense.
[src:active-directory/active-directory] Microsoft recommends using OUs rather than domains for structure and simplifying the implementation of policies and administration.
[src:active-directory/active-directory] The OU is the recommended level at which to apply group policies, which are Active Directory objects formally named group policy objects (GPOs), although policies can also be applied to domains or sites (see below).
[src:active-directory/active-directory] The OU is the level at which administrative powers are commonly delegated, but delegation can be performed on individual objects or attributes as well.
[src:active-directory/active-directory] Organizational units do not each have a separate namespace.
[src:active-directory/active-directory] As a consequence, for compatibility with Legacy NetBios implementations, user accounts with an identical SamAccountName are not allowed within the same domain even if the accounts objects are in separate OUs.
[src:active-directory/active-directory] This is because SamAccountName, a user object attribute, must be unique within the domain.
[src:active-directory/active-directory] However, two users in different OUs can have the same common name (CN), the name under which they are stored in the directory itself such as "fred.staff-ou.domain" and "fred.student-ou.domain", where "staff-ou" and "student-ou" are the OUs.
[src:active-directory/active-directory] Allowing for duplication of object names in the directory, or completely removing the use of NetBIOS names, would prevent backward compatibility with legacy software and equipment.
[src:active-directory/active-directory] However, disallowing duplicate object names in this way is a violation of the LDAP RFCs on which Active Directory is supposedly based.
[src:active-directory/active-directory] As the number of users in a domain increases, conventions such as "first initial, middle initial, last name" (Western order) or the reverse (Eastern order) fail for common family names like *Li* (李), *Smith* or *Garcia*.
[src:active-directory/active-directory] Workarounds include adding a digit to the end of the username.
[src:active-directory/active-directory] Alternatives include creating a separate ID system of unique employee/student ID numbers to use as account names in place of actual users' names and allowing users to nominate their preferred word sequence within an acceptable use policy.
[src:active-directory/active-directory] In Microsoft's Active Directory, OUs do not confer access permissions, and objects placed within OUs are not automatically assigned access privileges based on their containing OU.
[src:active-directory/active-directory] It represents a design limitation specific to Active Directory, and other competing directories, such as Novell NDS, can set access privileges through object placement within an OU.
[src:active-directory/active-directory] Active Directory requires a separate step for an administrator to assign an object in an OU as a group member also within that OU.
[src:active-directory/active-directory] Using only the OU location to determine access permissions is unreliable since the entity might not have been assigned to the group object for that OU yet.
[src:active-directory/active-directory] A common workaround for an Active Directory administrator is to write a custom PowerShell or Visual Basic script to automatically create and maintain a *user group* for each OU in their Directory.
[src:active-directory/active-directory] The scripts run periodically to update the group to match the OU's account membership.
[src:active-directory/active-directory] However, they cannot instantly update the security groups anytime the directory changes, as occurs in competing directories, as security is directly implemented into the Directory.
[src:active-directory/active-directory] Such groups are known as *shadow groups*.
[src:active-directory/active-directory] Once created, these shadow groups are selectable in place of the OU in the administrative tools.
[src:active-directory/active-directory] Microsoft's Server 2008 reference documentation mentions shadow groups but does not provide instructions on creating them.
[src:active-directory/active-directory] Additionally, there are no available server methods or console snap-ins for managing these groups.
[src:active-directory/active-directory] An organization must determine the structure of its information infrastructure by dividing it into one or more domains and top-level OUs.
[src:active-directory/active-directory] This decision is critical and can base on various models such as business units, geographical locations, IT service, object type, or a combination of these models.
[src:active-directory/active-directory] The immediate purpose of organizing OUs is to simplify administrative delegation and, secondarily, to apply group policies.
[src:active-directory/active-directory] While OUs serve as an administrative boundary, the forest itself is the only security boundary.
[src:active-directory/active-directory] All other domains must trust any administrator in the forest to maintain security.
[src:active-directory/active-directory] The Active Directory database is organized in *partitions*, each holding specific object types and following a particular replication pattern.
[src:active-directory/active-directory] Microsoft often refers to these partitions as 'naming contexts'.
[src:active-directory/active-directory] The 'Schema' partition defines object classes and attributes within the forest.
[src:active-directory/active-directory] The 'Configuration' partition contains information on the physical structure and configuration of the forest (such as the site topology).
[src:active-directory/active-directory] Both replicate all domains in the forest.
[src:active-directory/active-directory] The 'Domain' partition holds all objects created in that domain and replicates only within it.
[src:active-directory/active-directory] Some directory partitions store forest wide configuration information and schema information; other directory partitions store information specific to individual domains, such as users, groups, and organizational units.
[src:active-directory/active-directory] The Active Directory information is physically held on one or more peer domain controllers, replacing the NT PDC/BDC model.
[src:active-directory/active-directory] Each DC has a copy of the Active Directory.
[src:active-directory/active-directory] Member servers joined to Active Directory that are not domain controllers are called Member Servers.
[src:active-directory/active-directory] In the domain partition, a group of objects acts as copies of domain controllers set up as global catalogs.
[src:active-directory/active-directory] These global catalog servers offer a comprehensive list of all objects in the forest.
[src:active-directory/active-directory] Global Catalog servers replicate all objects from all domains to themselves, providing an international listing of entities in the forest.
[src:active-directory/active-directory] However, to minimize replication traffic and keep the GC's database small, only selected attributes of each object are replicated, called the *partial attribute set* (PAS).
[src:active-directory/active-directory] The PAS can be modified by modifying the schema and marking features for replication to the GC.
[src:active-directory/active-directory] Earlier versions of Windows used NetBIOS to communicate.
[src:active-directory/active-directory] Active Directory is fully integrated with DNS and requires TCP/IP—DNS.
[src:active-directory/active-directory] To fully operate, the DNS server must support SRV resource records, also known as service records.
[src:active-directory/active-directory] Active Directory uses multi-master replication to synchronize changes, meaning replicas pull changes from the server where the change occurred rather than being pushed to them.
[src:active-directory/active-directory] The Knowledge Consistency Checker (KCC) uses defined sites to manage traffic and create a replication topology of site links.
[src:active-directory/active-directory] Intra-site replication occurs frequently and automatically due to change notifications, which prompt peers to begin a pull replication cycle.
[src:active-directory/active-directory] Replication intervals between different sites are usually less consistent and don't usually use change notifications.
[src:active-directory/active-directory] However, it's possible to set it up to be the same as replication between locations on the same network if needed.
[src:active-directory/active-directory] Each DS3, T1, and ISDN link can have a cost, and the KCC alters the site link topology accordingly.
[src:active-directory/active-directory] Replication may occur transitively through several site links on same-protocol *site link bridges* if the price is low.
[src:active-directory/active-directory] However, KCC automatically costs a direct site-to-site link lower than transitive connections.
[src:active-directory/active-directory] A bridgehead server in each zone can send updates to other DCs in the exact location to replicate changes between sites.
[src:active-directory/active-directory] To configure replication for Active Directory zones, activate DNS in the domain based on the site.
[src:active-directory/active-directory] To replicate Active Directory, Remote Procedure Calls (RPC) over IP (RPC/IP) are used.
[src:active-directory/active-directory] SMTP is used to replicate between sites but only for modifications in the Schema, Configuration, or Partial Attribute Set (Global Catalog) GCs.
[src:active-directory/active-directory] It's not suitable for reproducing the default Domain partition.
[src:active-directory/active-directory] Generally, a network utilizing Active Directory has more than one licensed Windows server computer.
[src:active-directory/active-directory] Backup and restore of Active Directory are possible for a network with a single domain controller.
[src:active-directory/active-directory] However, Microsoft recommends more than one domain controller to provide automatic failover protection of the directory.
[src:active-directory/active-directory] Domain controllers are ideally single-purpose for directory operations only and should not run any other software or role.
[src:active-directory/active-directory] Since certain Microsoft products, like SQL Server and Exchange, can interfere with the operation of a domain controller, isolation of these products on additional Windows servers is advised.
[src:active-directory/active-directory] Combining them can complicate the configuration and troubleshooting of the domain controller or the other installed software more complex.
[src:active-directory/active-directory] If planning to implement Active Directory, a business should purchase multiple Windows server licenses to have at least two separate domain controllers.
[src:active-directory/active-directory] Administrators should consider additional domain controllers for performance or redundancy and individual servers for tasks like file storage, Exchange, and SQL Server since this will guarantee that all server roles are adequately supported.
[src:active-directory/active-directory] One way to lower the physical hardware costs is by using virtualization.
[src:active-directory/active-directory] However, for proper failover protection, Microsoft recommends not running multiple virtualized domain controllers on the same physical hardware.
[src:active-directory/active-directory] The Active-Directory database, the *directory store*, in Windows 2000 Server uses the JET Blue-based Extensible Storage Engine (ESE98).
[src:active-directory/active-directory] Each domain controller's database is limited to 16 terabytes and 2 billion objects (but only 1 billion security principals).
[src:active-directory/active-directory] Microsoft has created NTDS databases with more than 2 billion objects.
[src:active-directory/active-directory] NT4's Security Account Manager could support up to 40,000 objects.
[src:active-directory/active-directory] It has two main tables: the *data table* and the *link table*.
[src:active-directory/active-directory] Windows Server 2003 added a third main table for security descriptor single instancing.
[src:active-directory/active-directory] Programs may access the features of Active Directory via the COM interfaces provided by *Active Directory Service Interfaces*.
[src:active-directory/active-directory] To allow users in one domain to access resources in another, Active Directory uses trusts.
[src:active-directory/active-directory] Trusts inside a forest are automatically created when domains are created.
[src:active-directory/active-directory] The forest sets the default boundaries of trust, and implicit, transitive trust is automatic for all domains within a forest.
[src:active-directory/active-directory] One domain allows access to users on another domain, but the other domain does not allow access to users on the first domain.
[src:active-directory/active-directory] Two domains allow access to users on both domains.
[src:active-directory/active-directory] The domain that is trusted; whose users have access to the trusting domain.
[src:active-directory/active-directory] A trust that can extend beyond two domains to other trusted domains in the forest.
[src:active-directory/active-directory] A one way trust that does not extend beyond two domains.
[src:active-directory/active-directory] It is not transitive and is one way only.
[src:active-directory/active-directory] An explicit trust between domains in different trees or the same tree when a descendant/ancestor (child/parent) relationship does not exist between the two domains.
[src:active-directory/active-directory] Joins two domains in different trees, transitive, one- or two-way.
[src:active-directory/active-directory] Can be transitive or nontransitive (intransitive), one- or two-way.
[src:active-directory/active-directory] Connect to other forests or non-Active Directory domains.
[src:active-directory/active-directory] functionality level) 'bastion' forest, which issues time-limited group memberships.
[src:active-directory/active-directory] These management tools may not provide enough functionality for efficient workflow in large environments.
[src:active-directory/active-directory] Some third-party tools extend the administration and management capabilities.
[src:active-directory/active-directory] They provide essential features for a more convenient administration process, such as automation, reports, integration with other services, etc.
[src:active-directory/active-directory] The schema additions shipped with Windows Server 2003 R2 include attributes that map closely enough to RFC 2307 to be generally usable.
[src:active-directory/active-directory] The reference implementation of RFC 2307, nss_ldap and pam_ldap provided by PADL.com, support these attributes directly.
[src:active-directory/active-directory] The default schema for group membership complies with RFC 2307bis (proposed).
[src:active-directory/active-directory] Windows Server 2003 R2 includes a Microsoft Management Console snap-in that creates and edits the attributes.
[src:active-directory/active-directory] An alternative option is to use another directory service as non-Windows clients authenticate to this while Windows Clients authenticate to Active Directory.
[src:active-directory/active-directory] Non-Windows clients include 389 Directory Server (formerly Fedora Directory Server, FDS), ViewDS v7.2 XML Enabled Directory, and Sun Microsystems Sun Java System Directory Server.
[src:active-directory/active-directory] The latter two are both able to perform two-way synchronization with Active Directory and thus provide a "deflected" integration.
[src:active-directory/active-directory] Another option is to use OpenLDAP with its *translucent* overlay, which can extend entries in any remote LDAP server with additional attributes stored in a local database.
[src:active-directory/active-directory] Clients pointed at the local database see entries containing both the remote and local attributes, while the remote database remains completely untouched.
[src:active-directory/active-directory] Administration (querying, modifying, and monitoring) of Active Directory can be achieved via many scripting languages, including PowerShell, VBScript, JScript/JavaScript, Perl, Python, and Ruby.
[src:active-directory/active-directory] Free and non-free Active Directory administration tools can help to simplify and possibly automate Active Directory management tasks.
[src:active-directory/active-directory] Since October 2017 Amazon AWS offers integration with Microsoft Active Directory.
[src:active-directory/directory-service] In computing, a **directory service** or **name service** maps the names of network resources to their respective network addresses.
[src:active-directory/directory-service] It is a shared information infrastructure for locating, managing, administering and organizing everyday items and network resources, which can include volumes, folders, files, printers, users, groups, devices, telephone numbers and other objects.
[src:active-directory/directory-service] A directory service is a critical component of a network operating system.
[src:active-directory/directory-service] A **directory server** or name server is a server which provides such a service.
[src:active-directory/directory-service] Each resource on the network is considered an object by the directory server.
[src:active-directory/directory-service] Information about a particular resource is stored as a collection of attributes associated with that resource or object.
[src:active-directory/directory-service] A directory service defines a namespace for the network.
[src:active-directory/directory-service] The namespace is used to assign a *name* (unique identifier) to each of the objects.
[src:active-directory/directory-service] Directories typically have a set of rules determining how network resources are named and identified, which usually includes a requirement that the identifiers be unique and unambiguous.
[src:active-directory/directory-service] When using a directory service, a user does not have to remember the physical address of a network resource; providing a name locates the resource.
[src:active-directory/directory-service] Some directory services include access control provisions, limiting the availability of directory information to authorized users.
[src:active-directory/directory-service] Several things distinguish a directory service from a relational database.
[src:active-directory/directory-service] Attributes are sometimes multi-valued, allowing multiple naming attributes at one level (such as machine type and serial number concatenation, or multiple phone numbers for "work phone").
[src:active-directory/directory-service] Attributes and object classes are usually standardized throughout the industry; for example, X.500 attributes and classes are often formally registered with the IANA for their object ID.
[src:active-directory/directory-service] Therefore, directory applications try to reuse standard classes and attributes to maximize the benefit of existing directory-server software.
[src:active-directory/directory-service] Object instances are slotted into namespaces; each object class inherits from its parent object class (and ultimately from the root of the hierarchy), adding attributes to the must-may list.
[src:active-directory/directory-service] Directory services are often central to the security design of an IT system and have a correspondingly-fine granularity of access control.
[src:active-directory/directory-service] Replication and distribution have distinct meanings in the design and management of a directory service.
[src:active-directory/directory-service] Replication is used to indicate that the same directory namespace (the same objects) are copied to another directory server for redundancy and throughput reasons; the replicated namespace is governed by the same authority.
[src:active-directory/directory-service] Distribution is used to indicate that multiple directory servers in different namespaces are interconnected to form a distributed directory service; each namespace can be governed by a different authority.
[src:active-directory/directory-service] Directory services were part of an Open Systems Interconnection (OSI) initiative for common network standards and multi-vendor interoperability.
[src:active-directory/directory-service] During the 1980s, the ITU and ISO created the X.500 set of standards for directory services, initially to support the requirements of inter-carrier electronic messaging and network-name lookup.
[src:active-directory/directory-service] The Lightweight Directory Access Protocol (LDAP) is based on the X.500 directory-information services, using the TCP/IP stack and an X.500 Directory Access Protocol (DAP) string-encoding scheme on the Internet.
[src:active-directory/directory-service] Open-source tools to create directory services include OpenLDAP, the Kerberos protocol and Samba software, which can function as a Windows domain controller with Kerberos and LDAP back ends.
[src:active-directory/directory-service] Administration is by GOsa or Samba SWAT.
[src:active-directory/directory-service] Name services on Unix systems are typically configured through nsswitch.conf.
[src:active-directory/directory-service] Information from name services can be retrieved with getent.
[src:active-directory/domain-controller] A **domain controller** (**DC**) is a server that responds to security authentication requests within a computer network domain.
[src:active-directory/domain-controller] It is a network server that is responsible for allowing host access to domain resources.
[src:active-directory/domain-controller] It authenticates users, stores user account information and enforces security policy for a domain.
[src:active-directory/domain-controller] It is most commonly implemented in Microsoft Windows environments (see Domain controller (Windows)), where it is the centerpiece of the Windows Active Directory service.
[src:active-directory/domain-controller] However, non-Windows domain controllers can be established via identity management software such as Samba and Red Hat FreeIPA.
[src:active-directory/domain-controller] The software and operating system used to run a domain controller usually consists of several key components shared across platforms.
[src:active-directory/domain-controller] This includes the operating system (usually Windows Server or Linux), an LDAP service (Red Hat Directory Server, etc.), a network time service (ntpd, chrony, etc.), and a computer network authentication protocol (usually Kerberos).
[src:active-directory/domain-controller] Other components, such as a public key infrastructure (Active Directory Certificate Services, DogTag, OpenSSL) service and Domain Name System (Windows DNS or BIND) may also be included on the same server or on another domain-joined server.
[src:active-directory/domain-controller] Domain controllers are typically deployed as a cluster to ensure high-availability and maximize reliability.
[src:active-directory/domain-controller] In a Windows environment, one domain controller serves as the Primary Domain Controller (PDC) and all other servers promoted to domain controller status in the domain serve as a Backup Domain Controller (BDC).
[src:active-directory/domain-controller] In Unix-based environments, one machine serves as the master domain controller and others serve as replica domain controllers, periodically replicating database information from the main domain controller and storing it in a read-only format.
[src:active-directory/group-policy] Active Directory servers disseminate group policies by listing them in their LDAP directory under objects of class `groupPolicyContainer`.
[src:active-directory/group-policy] These refer to fileserver paths (attribute `gPCFileSysPath`) that store the actual group policy objects, typically in an SMB share \\*domain.com*\SYSVOL shared by the Active Directory server.
[src:active-directory/group-policy] If a group policy has registry settings, the associated file share will have a file `registry.pol` with the registry settings that the client needs to apply.
[src:active-directory/group-policy] The Policy Editor (`gpedit.msc`) is not provided on Home (& Starter) editions of Windows.
[src:active-directory/group-policy] Group Policies, in part, control what users can and cannot do on a computer system.
[src:active-directory/group-policy] For example, a Group Policy can be used to enforce a password complexity policy that prevents users from choosing an overly simple password.
[src:active-directory/group-policy] Other examples include: allowing or preventing unidentified users from remote computers to connect to a network share, or to block/restrict access to certain folders.
[src:active-directory/group-policy] A set of such configurations is called a Group Policy Object (GPO).
[src:active-directory/group-policy] As part of Microsoft's *IntelliMirror* technologies, Group Policy aims to reduce the cost of supporting users.
[src:active-directory/group-policy] IntelliMirror technologies relate to the management of disconnected machines or roaming users and include *roaming user profiles*, *folder redirection*, and *offline files*.
[src:active-directory/group-policy] To accomplish the goal of central management of a group of computers, machines should receive and enforce GPOs.
[src:active-directory/group-policy] A GPO that resides on a single machine only applies to that computer.
[src:active-directory/group-policy] To apply a GPO to a group of computers, Group Policy relies on Active Directory (or on third-party products like ZENworks Desktop Management) for distribution.
[src:active-directory/group-policy] Active Directory can distribute GPOs to computers which belong to a Windows domain.
[src:active-directory/group-policy] By default, Microsoft Windows refreshes its policy settings every 90 minutes with a random 30 minutes offset.
[src:active-directory/group-policy] On domain controllers, Microsoft Windows does so every five minutes.
[src:active-directory/group-policy] During the refresh, it discovers, fetches and applies all GPOs that apply to the machine and to logged-on users.
[src:active-directory/group-policy] Some settings - such as those for automated software installation, drive mappings, startup scripts or logon scripts - only apply during startup or user logon.
[src:active-directory/group-policy] Since Windows XP, users can manually initiate a refresh of the group policy by using the `gpupdate` command from a command prompt.
[src:active-directory/group-policy] **Site** - Any Group Policies associated with the *Active Directory site* in which the computer resides.
[src:active-directory/group-policy] (An Active Directory site is a logical grouping of computers, intended to facilitate management of those computers based on their physical proximity.) If multiple policies are linked to a site, they are processed in the order set by the administrator.
[src:active-directory/group-policy] **Domain** - Any Group Policies associated with the Windows domain in which the computer resides.
[src:active-directory/group-policy] If multiple policies are linked to a domain, they are processed in the order set by the administrator.
[src:active-directory/group-policy] **Organizational Unit** - Group policies assigned to the *Active Directory organizational unit (OU)* in which the computer or user are placed.
[src:active-directory/group-policy] (OUs are logical units that help organizing and managing a group of users, computers or other Active Directory objects.) If multiple policies are linked to an OU, they are processed in the order set by the administrator.
[src:active-directory/group-policy] The resulting Group Policy settings applied to a given computer or user are known as the Resultant Set of Policy (RSoP).
[src:active-directory/group-policy] RSoP information may be displayed for both computers and users using the `gpresult` command.
[src:active-directory/group-policy] A policy setting inside a hierarchical structure is ordinarily passed from parent to children, and from children to grandchildren, and so forth.
[src:active-directory/group-policy] It can be blocked or enforced to control what policies are applied at each level.
[src:active-directory/group-policy] If a higher level administrator (enterprise administrator) creates a policy that has inheritance blocked by a lower level administrator (domain administrator), this policy will still be processed.
[src:active-directory/group-policy] Where a Group Policy Preference Settings is configured and there is also an equivalent Group Policy Setting configured, then the value of the Group Policy Setting will take precedence.
[src:active-directory/group-policy] The *System Policy Editor* was first introduced in Windows NT 4.0 Server.
[src:active-directory/group-policy] Later, Windows 2000 Professional and Windows 2000 Server introduced *Group Policy Editor* based on Microsoft Management Console.
[src:active-directory/group-policy] Group Policy Preferences are a way for the administrator to set policies that are not mandatory, but optional for the user or computer.
[src:active-directory/group-policy] There is a set of group policy setting extensions that were previously known as PolicyMaker.
[src:active-directory/group-policy] Microsoft bought PolicyMaker and then integrated them with Windows Server 2008.
[src:active-directory/group-policy] Microsoft has since released a migration tool that allows users to migrate PolicyMaker items to Group Policy Preferences.
[src:active-directory/group-policy] Group Policy Preferences adds a number of new configuration items.
[src:active-directory/group-policy] These items also have a number of additional targeting options that can be used to granularly control the application of these setting items.
[src:active-directory/group-policy] Group Policy Preferences are compatible with x86 and x64 versions of Windows XP, Windows Server 2003, and Windows Vista with the addition of the Client Side Extensions (also known as CSE).
[src:active-directory/group-policy] Client Side Extensions are now included in Windows Server 2008, Windows 7, and Windows Server 2008 R2.
[src:active-directory/group-policy] Originally, Group Policies were modified using the Group Policy Edit tool that was integrated with Active Directory Users and Computers Microsoft Management Console (MMC) snap-in, but it was later split into a separate MMC snap-in called the Group Policy Management Console (GPMC).
[src:active-directory/group-policy] The GPMC is now a user component in Windows Server 2008 and Windows Server 2008 R2 and is provided as a download as part of the Remote Server Administration Tools for Windows Vista and Windows 7.
[src:active-directory/group-policy] Microsoft has also released a tool to make changes to Group Policy called Advanced Group Policy Management (a.k.a.
[src:active-directory/group-policy] This tool is available for any organization that has licensed the Microsoft Desktop Optimization Pack (a.k.a.
[src:active-directory/group-policy] This advanced tool allows administrators to have a check in/out process for modification Group Policy Objects, track changes to Group Policy Objects, and implement approval workflows for changes to Group Policy Objects.
[src:active-directory/group-policy] AGPM consists of two parts - server and client.
[src:active-directory/group-policy] The server is a Windows Service that stores its Group Policy Objects in an archive located on the same computer or a network share.
[src:active-directory/group-policy] The client is a snap-in to the Group Policy Management Console, and connects to the AGPM server.
[src:active-directory/group-policy] Configuration of the client is performed via Group Policy.
[src:active-directory/group-policy] Administrative Templates are a feature of Group Policy, a Microsoft technology for centralized management of machines and users in an Active Directory environment.
[src:active-directory/group-policy] Administrative Templates facilitate the management of registry-based policy.
[src:active-directory/group-policy] An ADM file is used to describe both the user interface presented to the Group Policy administrator and the registry keys that should be updated on the target machines.
[src:active-directory/group-policy] An ADM file is a text file with a specific syntax which describes both the interface and the registry values which will be changed if the policy is enabled or disabled.
[src:active-directory/group-policy] ADM files are consumed by the Group Policy Object Editor (GPEdit).
[src:active-directory/group-policy] Windows XP Service Pack 2 shipped with five ADM files (system.adm, inetres.adm, wmplayer.adm, conf.adm and wuau.adm).
[src:active-directory/group-policy] These are merged into a unified "namespace" in GPEdit and presented to the administrator under the Administrative Templates node (for both machine and user policy).
[src:active-directory/group-policy] View Filtering must be turned off in order to see custom preference settings (such as this example) in the Group Policy Editor.
[src:active-directory/group-policy] ADM files shipped with Microsoft operating systems include descriptions of policy settings for not just that platform but for all other platforms on which Group Policy is supported.
[src:active-directory/group-policy] For example, the Windows XP Service Pack 2 ADM files described policy settings not just for this platform but also for Windows 2000 and Windows Server 2003.
[src:active-directory/group-policy] This approach allows management of machines that are running an operating system other than that on which GPEdit is used.
[src:active-directory/group-policy] By default, ADM files are stored in each GPO, within Sysvol on domain controllers.
[src:active-directory/group-policy] This creates a simple and effective model for replicating ADM files across domain controllers (which is handled by the File Replication Service).
[src:active-directory/group-policy] However, in some instances this can cause operational issues.
[src:active-directory/group-policy] To this end, various policy settings are available to manage the manner in which ADM files are read and stored.
[src:active-directory/group-policy] These are described in Microsoft's KB article 816662.
[src:active-directory/group-policy] Starting with Windows Vista, ADM files have mostly been replaced with ADMX files (and their associated language-specific ADML files).
[src:active-directory/group-policy] The ADMX file is structured in standard XML format, whereas the ADM files used a proprietary format.
[src:active-directory/group-policy] Group Policy settings are enforced voluntarily by the targeted applications.
[src:active-directory/group-policy] In many cases, this merely consists of disabling the user interface for a particular function.
[src:active-directory/group-policy] Alternatively, a malevolent user can modify or interfere with the application so that it cannot successfully read its Group Policy settings, thus enforcing potentially lower security defaults or even returning arbitrary values.
[src:active-directory/group-policy] Group Policy was enhanced following its initial release in Windows 2000.
[src:active-directory/group-policy] For example, Windows XP has introduced a new feature called Group Policy Update which replaced the `secedit` command.
[src:active-directory/group-policy] This feature allows an administrator to force a group policy update on all computers with accounts in a particular Organizational Unit.
[src:active-directory/group-policy] This overrides the default scheduled task on the computer which runs the `gpupdate` command within 90 minutes, adjusted by a random offset to avoid overloading the domain controller.
[src:active-directory/group-policy] Group Policy Infrastructure Status was introduced, which can report when any Group Policy Objects are not replicated correctly amongst domain controllers.
[src:active-directory/group-policy] Group Policy Results Report also has a new feature that times the execution of individual components when doing a Group Policy Update.
[src:active-directory/identity-and-access-management] The terms "identity management" (IdM) and "identity and access management" are used interchangeably in the area of identity access management.
[src:active-directory/identity-and-access-management] Identity-management systems, products, applications and platforms manage identifying and ancillary data about entities that include individuals, computer-related hardware, and software applications.
[src:active-directory/identity-and-access-management] IdM covers issues such as how users gain an identity, the roles, and sometimes the permissions that identity grants, the protection of that identity, and the technologies supporting that protection (e.g., network protocols, digital certificates, passwords, etc.).
[src:active-directory/identity-and-access-management] Identity management (IdM) is the task of controlling information about users on computers.
[src:active-directory/identity-and-access-management] Such information includes information that authenticates the identity of a user, and information that describes data and actions they are authorized to access and/or perform.
[src:active-directory/identity-and-access-management] It also includes the management of descriptive information about the user and how and by whom that information can be accessed and modified.
[src:active-directory/identity-and-access-management] In addition to users, managed entities typically include hardware and network resources and even applications.
[src:active-directory/identity-and-access-management] The diagram below shows the relationship between the configuration and operation phases of IAM, as well as the distinction between identity management and access management.
[src:active-directory/identity-and-access-management] Access control is the enforcement of access rights defined as part of access authorization.
[src:active-directory/identity-and-access-management] Digital identity is an entity's online presence, encompassing personal identifying information (PII) and ancillary information.
[src:active-directory/identity-and-access-management] See OECD and NIST guidelines on protecting PII.
[src:active-directory/identity-and-access-management] It can be interpreted as the codification of identity names and attributes of a physical instance in a way that facilitates processing.
[src:active-directory/identity-and-access-management] A general model of identity can be constructed from a small set of axioms, for example that all identities in a given namespace are unique, or that such identities bear a specific relationship to corresponding entities in the real world.
[src:active-directory/identity-and-access-management] Such an axiomatic model expresses "pure identity" in the sense that the model is not constrained by a specific application context.
[src:active-directory/identity-and-access-management] In general, an entity (real or virtual) can have multiple identities and each identity can encompass multiple attributes, some of which are unique within a given name space.
[src:active-directory/identity-and-access-management] The diagram below illustrates the conceptual relationship between identities and entities, as well as between identities and their attributes.
[src:active-directory/identity-and-access-management] In most theoretical and all practical models of digital identity, a given identity object consists of a finite set of properties (attribute values).
[src:active-directory/identity-and-access-management] These properties record information about the object, either for purposes external to the model or to operate the model, for example in classification and retrieval.
[src:active-directory/identity-and-access-management] A "pure identity" model is strictly not concerned with the external semantics of these properties.
[src:active-directory/identity-and-access-management] The most common departure from "pure identity" in practice occurs with properties intended to assure some aspect of identity, for example a digital signature or software token which the model may use internally to verify some aspect of the identity in satisfaction of an external purpose.
[src:active-directory/identity-and-access-management] To the extent that the model expresses such semantics internally, it is not a pure model.
[src:active-directory/identity-and-access-management] Contrast this situation with properties that might be externally used for purposes of information security such as managing access or entitlement, but which are simply stored, maintained and retrieved, without special treatment by the model.
[src:active-directory/identity-and-access-management] The absence of external semantics within the model qualifies it as a "pure identity" model.
[src:active-directory/identity-and-access-management] Identity management can thus be defined as a set of operations on a given identity model, or more generally, as a set of capabilities with reference to it.
[src:active-directory/identity-and-access-management] In practice, identity management often expands to express how model content is to be provisioned and reconciled among multiple identity models.
[src:active-directory/identity-and-access-management] The process of reconciling accounts may also be referred to as de-provisioning.
[src:active-directory/identity-and-access-management] User access enables users to assume a specific digital identity across applications, which enables access controls to be assigned and evaluated against this identity.
[src:active-directory/identity-and-access-management] The use of a single identity for a given user across multiple systems eases tasks for administrators and users.
[src:active-directory/identity-and-access-management] It simplifies access monitoring and verification, and allows the organizations to minimize excessive privileges granted to one user.
[src:active-directory/identity-and-access-management] Ensuring user access security is crucial in this process, as it involves protecting the integrity and confidentiality of user credentials and preventing unauthorized access.
[src:active-directory/identity-and-access-management] Implementing robust authentication mechanisms, such as multi-factor authentication (MFA), regular security audits, and strict access controls, helps safeguard user identities and sensitive data.
[src:active-directory/identity-and-access-management] User access can be tracked from initiation to termination of user access.
[src:active-directory/identity-and-access-management] When organizations deploy an identity management process or system, their motivation is normally not primarily to manage a set of identities, but rather to grant appropriate access rights to those entities via their identities.
[src:active-directory/identity-and-access-management] In other words, access management is normally the motivation for identity management and the two sets of processes are consequently closely related.
[src:active-directory/identity-and-access-management] Organizations continue to add services for both internal users and by customers.
[src:active-directory/identity-and-access-management] Many such services require identity management to properly provide these services.
[src:active-directory/identity-and-access-management] Increasingly, identity management has been partitioned from application functions so that a single identity can serve many or even all of an organization's activities.
[src:active-directory/identity-and-access-management] For internal use identity management is evolving to control access to all digital assets, including devices, network equipment, servers, portals, content, applications and/or products.
[src:active-directory/identity-and-access-management] Services often require access to extensive information about a user, including address books, preferences, entitlements and contact information.
[src:active-directory/identity-and-access-management] Since much of this information is subject to privacy and/or confidentiality requirements, controlling access to it is vital.
[src:active-directory/identity-and-access-management] Identity federation comprises one or more systems that share user access and allow users to log in based on authenticating against one of the systems participating in the federation.
[src:active-directory/identity-and-access-management] This trust between several systems is often known as a "circle of trust".
[src:active-directory/identity-and-access-management] In this setup, one system acts as the identity provider (IdP) and other systems act as service providers (SPs).
[src:active-directory/identity-and-access-management] When a user needs to access some service controlled by SP, they first authenticate against the IdP.
[src:active-directory/identity-and-access-management] Upon successful authentication, the IdP sends a secure "assertion" to the SP.
[src:active-directory/identity-and-access-management] "SAML assertions, specified using a markup language intended for describing security assertions, can be used by a verifier to make a statement to a relying party about the identity of a claimant.
[src:active-directory/identity-and-access-management] In addition to creation, deletion, modification of user identity data either assisted or self-service, identity management controls ancillary entity data for use by applications, such as contact information or location.
[src:active-directory/identity-and-access-management] Putting personal information onto computer networks necessarily raises privacy concerns.
[src:active-directory/identity-and-access-management] Absent proper protections, the data may be used to implement a surveillance society.
[src:active-directory/identity-and-access-management] Social web and online social networking services make heavy use of identity management.
[src:active-directory/identity-and-access-management] Helping users decide how to manage access to their personal information has become an issue of broad concern.
[src:active-directory/identity-and-access-management] Research related to the management of identity covers disciplines such as technology, social sciences, humanities and the law.
[src:active-directory/identity-and-access-management] Decentralized identity management is identity management based on decentralized identifiers (DIDs).
[src:active-directory/identity-and-access-management] Within the Seventh Research Framework Programme of the European Union from 2007 to 2013, several new projects related to Identity Management started.
[src:active-directory/identity-and-access-management] The PICOS Project investigates and develops a state-of-the-art platform for providing trust, privacy and identity management in mobile communities.
[src:active-directory/identity-and-access-management] SWIFT focuses on extending identity functions and federation to the network while addressing usability and privacy concerns and leverages identity technology as a key to integrate service and transport infrastructures for the benefit of users and the providers.
[src:active-directory/identity-and-access-management] Ongoing projects include Future of Identity in the Information Society (FIDIS), GUIDE, and PRIME.
[src:active-directory/identity-and-access-management] In each organization there is normally a role or department that is responsible for managing the schema of digital identities of their staff and their own objects, which are represented by object identities or object identifiers (OID).
[src:active-directory/identity-and-access-management] The organizational policies and processes and procedures related to the oversight of identity management are sometimes referred to as *Identity Governance and Administration* (IGA).
[src:active-directory/identity-and-access-management] How effectively and appropriately such tools are used falls within scope of broader governance, risk management, and compliance regimes.
[src:active-directory/identity-and-access-management] An **identity-management system** refers to an information system, or to a set of technologies that can be used for enterprise or cross-network identity management.
[src:active-directory/identity-and-access-management] Identity and access management systems are central to meeting regulatory requirements across multiple sectors that mandate controls over who can access sensitive information.
[src:active-directory/identity-and-access-management] NIST Special Publication 800-53 includes comprehensive identity and access management controls in the AC (Access Control) and IA (Identification and Authentication) control families, providing the reference framework for federal agency IAM implementations.
[src:active-directory/kerberos-protocol] Kerberos builds on symmetric-key cryptography and requires a trusted third party, and optionally may use public-key cryptography during certain phases of authentication.
[src:active-directory/kerberos-protocol] The protocol was named after the character *Cerberus*, also spelled *Kerberos*, from Greek mythology, the ferocious three-headed guard dog of Hades.
[src:active-directory/kerberos-protocol] The Massachusetts Institute of Technology (MIT) developed Kerberos in 1988 to protect network services provided by Project Athena.
[src:active-directory/kerberos-protocol] Its first version was primarily designed by Steve Miller and Clifford Neuman based on the earlier Needham–Schroeder symmetric-key protocol.
[src:active-directory/kerberos-protocol] Kerberos versions 1 through 3 were experimental and not released outside of MIT.
[src:active-directory/kerberos-protocol] Kerberos version 4, the first public version, was released on January 24, 1989.
[src:active-directory/kerberos-protocol] Since Kerberos 4 was developed in the United States, and since it used the Data Encryption Standard (DES) encryption algorithm, U.S. export control restrictions prevented it from being exported to other countries.
[src:active-directory/kerberos-protocol] MIT created an exportable version of Kerberos 4 with all encryption code removed, called "Bones".
[src:active-directory/kerberos-protocol] Eric Young of Australia's Bond University reimplemented DES into Bones, in a version called "eBones", which could be freely used in any country.
[src:active-directory/kerberos-protocol] Sweden's Royal Institute of Technology released another reimplementation called KTH-KRB.
[src:active-directory/kerberos-protocol] Neuman and John Kohl published version 5 in 1993 with the intention of overcoming existing limitations and security problems.
[src:active-directory/kerberos-protocol] Version 5 appeared as RFC 1510, which was then made obsolete by RFC 4120 in 2005.
[src:active-directory/kerberos-protocol] In 2005, the Internet Engineering Task Force (IETF) Kerberos working group updated specifications.
[src:active-directory/kerberos-protocol] MIT makes an implementation of Kerberos freely available, under copyright permissions similar to those used for BSD.
[src:active-directory/kerberos-protocol] In 2007, MIT formed the Kerberos Consortium to foster continued development.
[src:active-directory/kerberos-protocol] Founding sponsors include vendors such as Oracle, Apple Inc., Google, Microsoft, Centrify Corporation and TeamF1 Inc., and academic institutions such as the Royal Institute of Technology in Sweden, Stanford University, MIT, and vendors such as CyberSafe offering commercially supported versions.
[src:active-directory/kerberos-protocol] The client authenticates itself to the **Authentication Server (AS)** which is part of the **key distribution center** **(KDC)**.
[src:active-directory/kerberos-protocol] The KDC issues a **ticket-granting ticket (TGT)**, which is time stamped and encrypts it using the **ticket-granting service's (TGS)** secret key and returns the encrypted result to the user's workstation.
[src:active-directory/kerberos-protocol] This is done infrequently, typically at user logon; the TGT expires at some point although it may be transparently renewed by the user's session manager while they are logged in.
[src:active-directory/kerberos-protocol] When the client needs to communicate with a service on another node (a "principal", in Kerberos parlance), the client sends the TGT to the TGS, which is another component of the KDC and usually shares the same host as the authentication server.
[src:active-directory/kerberos-protocol] The service must have already been registered with the TGS with a **Service Principal Name (SPN)**.
[src:active-directory/kerberos-protocol] The client uses the SPN to request access to this service.
[src:active-directory/kerberos-protocol] After verifying that the TGT is valid and that the user is permitted to access the requested service, the TGS issues a **service ticket (ST)** and session keys to the client.
[src:active-directory/kerberos-protocol] The client then sends the ticket to the **service server (SS)** along with its service request.
[src:active-directory/kerberos-protocol] The protocol is described in detail below.
[src:active-directory/kerberos-protocol] The client transforms the password into a symmetric key using a one-way hash or standard key derivation function, depending on the cipher suite used.
[src:active-directory/kerberos-protocol] In modern Kerberos (v5), the client often uses this key to encrypt a current timestamp.
[src:active-directory/kerberos-protocol] This encrypted timestamp is sent to the AS along with the username as "pre-authentication" to prove the user knows the password before the AS issues any tickets, preventing offline brute-force attacks.
[src:active-directory/kerberos-protocol] The AS checks to see whether the client is in its database.
[src:active-directory/kerberos-protocol] Once the client receives messages A and B, it attempts to decrypt message A with the secret key generated from the password entered by the user.
[src:active-directory/kerberos-protocol] If the user entered password does not match the password in the AS database, the client's secret key will be different and thus unable to decrypt message A.
[src:active-directory/kerberos-protocol] With a valid password and secret key the client decrypts message A to obtain the *Client/TGS Session Key*.
[src:active-directory/kerberos-protocol] This session key is used for further communications with the TGS.
[src:active-directory/kerberos-protocol] (Note: The client cannot decrypt Message B, as it is encrypted using TGS's secret key.) At this point, the client has enough information to authenticate itself to the TGS.
[src:active-directory/kerberos-protocol] Upon receiving messages C and D, the TGS retrieves message B out of message C.
[src:active-directory/kerberos-protocol] It decrypts message B using the TGS secret key.
[src:active-directory/kerberos-protocol] This gives it the *Client/TGS Session Key* and the client ID (both are in the TGT).
[src:active-directory/kerberos-protocol] The SS decrypts the ticket (message E) using its own secret key to retrieve the *Client/Server Session Key*.
[src:active-directory/kerberos-protocol] The client decrypts the confirmation (message H) using the *Client/Server Session Key* and checks whether the timestamp is correct.
[src:active-directory/kerberos-protocol] If so, then the client can trust the server and can start issuing service requests to the server.
[src:active-directory/kerberos-protocol] The server provides the requested services to the client.
[src:active-directory/kerberos-protocol] Windows 2000 and later versions use Kerberos as their default authentication method.
[src:active-directory/kerberos-protocol] Some Microsoft additions to the Kerberos suite of protocols are documented in RFC 3244 "Microsoft Windows 2000 Kerberos Change Password and Set Password Protocols".
[src:active-directory/kerberos-protocol] RFC 4757 documents Microsoft's use of the RC4 cipher.
[src:active-directory/kerberos-protocol] While Microsoft uses and extends the Kerberos protocol, it does not use the MIT software.
[src:active-directory/kerberos-protocol] Kerberos is used as the preferred authentication method: in general, joining a client to a Windows domain means enabling Kerberos as the default protocol for authentications from that client to services in the Windows domain and all domains with trust relationships to that domain.
[src:active-directory/kerberos-protocol] In contrast, when either client or server or both are not joined to a domain (or not part of the same trusted domain environment), Windows will instead use NTLM for authentication between client and server.
[src:active-directory/kerberos-protocol] Internet web applications can enforce Kerberos as an authentication method for domain-joined clients by using APIs provided under SSPI.
[src:active-directory/kerberos-protocol] Microsoft Windows and Windows Server include setspn, a command-line utility that can be used to read, modify, or delete the Service Principal Names (SPN) for an Active Directory service account.
[src:active-directory/kerberos-protocol] Many Unix-like operating systems, including FreeBSD, Apple's macOS, Red Hat Enterprise Linux, Oracle's Solaris, IBM's AIX, HP-UX and others, include software for Kerberos authentication of users or services.
[src:active-directory/kerberos-protocol] A variety of non-Unix like operating systems such as z/OS, IBM i and OpenVMS also feature Kerberos support.
[src:active-directory/kerberos-protocol] Embedded implementation of the Kerberos V authentication protocol for client agents and network services running on embedded platforms is also available from companies.
[src:active-directory/kerberos-protocol] The Data Encryption Standard (DES) cipher can be used in combination with Kerberos, but is no longer an Internet standard because it is weak.
[src:active-directory/kerberos-protocol] Security vulnerabilities exist in products that implement legacy versions of Kerberos which lack support for newer encryption ciphers like AES.
